"id":"mk19_bb_rm_s13",
"title":{
"__html":"Infectious Arthritis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"01ab44",
"children":[
"Infectious Arthritis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_rm_s13_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f4baa7",
"children":[
"Infectious arthritis typically presents with pain, swelling, warmth, and erythema with fever and constitutional symptoms. Previously damaged joints are at increased risk for involvement; new inflammation of a single joint in a patient with well-controlled inflammatory arthritis is highly suggestive."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"820d79",
"children":[
"Physical examination shows loss of active and passive range of motion. Skin examination can reveal signs suggesting gonococcal infection (pustular skin lesions) or potential portals of entry for pathogens (scratches, bites, or foreign bodies)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4ab217",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Common organisms causing infectious arthritis:"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"541910",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Gram-positive organisms"
]
},
" are the most common causes of infectious arthritis in adults. ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Staphylococcus aureus"
]
},
" is the most common organism, regardless of age or underlying risk factors."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a9c9d7",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Gonococcal arthritis"
]
},
" is the most common form of bacterial arthritis in young, sexually active persons."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"13990e",
"children":[
"Disseminated gonococcal infection can produce two distinct syndromes: arthritis-dermatitis syndrome and purulent gonococcal arthritis."
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"4ebc2e",
"children":[
"Patients with the ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"arthritis-dermatitis syndrome"
]
},
" have cutaneous lesions that progress from papules or macules to pustules that are sterile on culture, tenosynovitis, and polyarthralgia. Fever and chills are common. Obtain ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"nucleic acid amplification testing",
"children":[
"NAAT"
]
},
" on samples from genital, rectal, and pharyngeal sites."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"2f7c6a",
"children":[
"Patients with ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"purulent gonococcal arthritis"
]
},
" do not have systemic features or dermatitis. Synovial fluid cultures for ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"N. gonorrhoeae"
]
},
" are positive in 50% of infected patients."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f3fa62",
"children":[
"Evaluate for deficiencies in terminal complement components for patients with recurrent episodes of disseminated gonococcal infection."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"bef7ba",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Less common causes of infectious arthritis:"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"48f6dd",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Gram-negative infections"
]
},
" are more common in prosthetic joints; older, immunosuppressed, and postoperative patients; and in those with IV catheters."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1aefa2",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Tuberculous arthritis"
]
},
" is typically an indolent, monoarticular arthritis involving the hip or knee; it does not cause systemic features. Gram stain and culture of synovial fluid are positive in only 50%. Diagnosis is made by synovial biopsy."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"3af465",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Lyme arthritis"
]
},
" is a late-stage manifestation of Lyme disease most commonly affecting the knee."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"372549",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Fungal arthritis"
]
},
" typically manifests as subacute monoarthritis in patients with a systemic fungal infection."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"580878",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Always select arthrocentesis with Gram stain; polarized microscopy for crystals; cell count; and differential for an acutely swollen, painful joint (monoarthritis)."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"bf6570",
"children":[
"Infectious arthritis can develop in patients with gout or acute ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"calcium pyrophosphate",
"children":[
"CPP"
]
},
" crystal arthritis (pseudogout), and the presence of crystals in synovial fluid does not exclude a concomitant infection."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"545f83",
"children":[
"X-rays are not helpful in the early diagnosis of acute native joint infection."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_rm_s13_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a83836",
"children":[
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Begin immediate empiric antibiotic therapy for suspected bacterial arthritis plus perform joint drainage. Drain reaccumulated purulent joint fluid. "
]
},
"Manage infected prosthetic joints with surgery plus antibiotics, usually for 3 to 6 weeks."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_rm_s13_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8f0249",
"children":[
"Suspect tubercular or fungal arthritis if the appropriate empiric antibacterial therapy is unsuccessful."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_rm_s13_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0e593a",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 28-year-old woman has a 9-day history of arthritis, fever, and chills followed by pain and swelling of the second and third ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"metacarpophalangeal",
"children":[
"MCP"
]
},
" joints. As swelling resolved, the right wrist became inflamed. As the wrist improved, the right knee became inflamed. She also has a 5-mm vesicle surrounded by erythema on the forearm."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0e5eac",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose disseminated gonococcal infection. For management, select ceftriaxone for gonorrhea and doxycycline for empiric treatment of chlamydia."
]
}
]
}
]
},
